**Project Details**

[MusicBlocks-v4](https://github.com/sugarlabs/musicblocks-v4) is a comprehensive overhaul of the original [MusicBlocks-v3](https://github.com/sugarlabs/musicblocks) project, designed to provide a more sustainable and modern platform for exploring musical concepts through visual programming. The transition from version 3 to version 4 involves significant technological advancements and feature enhancements

The MusicBlocks-v4 is comprised of 2 important modules which are comprised in the form of repositories:

1. [MusicBlocks-v4](https://github.com/sugarlabs/musicblocks-v4) Masonry Module: MusicBlocks-v4 is built using contemporary technologies, including React with Functional Components and hooks, TypeScript, JavaScript DOM API for event-based DOM manipulation, Canvas API for rendering blocks, and state management solutions like Zustand. This shift addresses sustainability concerns associated with the previous reliance on HTML, CSS, and Vanilla JavaScript.

2. [MusicBlocks-v4-lib](https://github.com/sugarlabs/musicblocks-v4-lib) Module: The core framework of Music Blocks v4 is encapsulated in the MusicBlocks-v4-lib repository. This framework defines the business logic and rules for program syntax elements (literals, expressions, statements, blocks, functions) and maintains the Syntax Tree representing a program. It also includes an Execution Engine that handles the runtime behavior of programs, aiming for low-overhead interpretation supporting pseudo real-time and concurrency.

The **Music Blocks v4** project is a reconstruction of the classic Music Blocks platform, a visual music programming environment, utilizing TypeScript, React, and contemporary tooling such as Vite, Zustand, and Jest. The proposal is centered around adding the missing "Masonry Module," a main feature that allows users to construct music programs by dragging, dropping, and linking interactive SVG-based blocks like Start, Rhythm, Note, Pitch, and Instrument. The module will feature configurable block rendering, a block palette with categories, a dynamic workspace, and utilities to visually and in-memory manage program structure. With performance, accessibility (through React-Aria), and modular design in mind, the Masonry Module will put v4 on par with the legacy version while greatly improving maintainability, user experience, and developer productivity. This project will simplify and make more intuitive the process of creating music by means of a rich, interactive web application.

For the Masonry Module to reach its full potential, key enhancements must be made to elevate the user experience, improve performance, and refine the system’s flexibility. My GSoC proposal for Music Blocks focuses on bringing substantial improvements to this module.

**I am deeply committed to developing and refining the Masonry Module end-to-end, ensuring that users can seamlessly build, experiment, and refine their musical creations.**

**Breakdown of Masonry Module:**

The Masonry module is a streamlined module to previous years’ [Project-Builder](https://github.com/sugarlabs/musicblocks-v4/tree/develop/modules/code-builder) Module. The work done last year creates the [Masonry](https://github.com/sugarlabs/musicblocks-v4/tree/gsoc-2024/week-11-12/modules/masonry) module which refactors the whole Project-Builder module.This module reorganized brick classes to align with their intended properties like inline editing and connection points. It also fixed bounding box rendering issues in the Masonry Module and integrated Storybook for visual testing.  
The folder structure for Masonry Module ensures clarity and maintainability, separating concerns like core logic, testing, and interactive visualization. The screenshot below is of the folder breakdown for the Masonry Module:  
The Masonry module consists of 3 main folders:

1. [**/masonry/src**](https://github.com/sugarlabs/musicblocks-v4/tree/gsoc-2024/week-11-12/modules/masonry/src) \- The **src/** folder in the Masonry module leverages Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) concepts to structure and organize the code effectively. By utilizing classes and interfaces, it ensures that different brick types and their behaviors are abstracted into well-defined entities.

   This section will breakdown the following important folders which encapsulates the essence of brick generation![][image1]

   1. [**@types**](https://github.com/sugarlabs/musicblocks-v4/tree/gsoc-2024/week-11-12/modules/masonry/src/%40types)**:** The **brick.d.ts** file defines core data types like TBrickType, TExtent, and TCoords to maintain consistency across bricks. It establishes interfaces for various brick types (e.g., IBrick, IBrickData, IBrickStatement) to ensure a modular design. These interfaces define brick properties, including connection points, rendering attributes, and dynamic behaviors. Bricks are classified by their TBrickKind (instruction or argument) and TBrickType (data, expression, statement, block), with geometry defined by TExtent and TCoords for size and position. The file structures how bricks are rendered, connected, and nested, with specific properties like SVG paths, labels, and scaling.

   2. [**Brick**](https://github.com/sugarlabs/musicblocks-v4/tree/gsoc-2024/week-11-12/modules/masonry/src/brick)**:** This folder expands into 3 more folders which are:

      **i. [masonry/src/brick/design0/](https://github.com/sugarlabs/musicblocks-v4/tree/gsoc-2024/week-11-12/modules/masonry/src/brick/design0):** The **design0/** folder in the Masonry module defines the core class-based logic for various brick types in the MusicBlocks v4 system, including block bricks, data bricks, expression bricks, and statement bricks. Each brick type is modularly structured, inheriting from abstract base classes like BrickModelBlock, BrickModelData and BrickModelExpression ensuring consistency in behavior while providing specific functionalities. The BrickBlock.ts defines higher-level constructs like loops and functions, allowing nesting, while BrickData.ts stores values that other bricks use, with support for dynamic values. BrickExpression.ts handles mathematical and logical operations, connecting to other bricks for evaluation, and BrickStatement.ts defines action-triggering bricks like loops and conditionals that modify the system state. The BrickFactory.ts dynamically creates these brick types using a factory pattern, ensuring modularity, while managing each brick’s lifecycle and guaranteeing unique IDs to prevent redundant creations. Together, these files enable the creation, manipulation, and rendering of bricks in a structured and interactive way, supporting the block-based programming interface of **MusicBlocks-v4** . Zustand is also used for state management, specifically to manage and store the dynamic coordinates (x,y) of bricks in the workspace. Unlike more complex state management solutions like Redux or React Context, Zustand is lightweight, easy to integrate, and offers a simple API for managing global state with minimal boilerplate.

      **ii. [masonry/src/brick/stories](https://github.com/sugarlabs/musicblocks-v4/tree/gsoc-2024/week-11-12/modules/masonry/src/brick/stories):**The **stories/components** folder in the Brick module is integral to rendering and testing the various types of bricks in the MusicBlocks v4 system within the Storybook environment. This folder contains key React components like BrickBlock.tsx, BrickData.tsx, BrickExpression.tsx, BrickStatement.tsx and BrickWrapper.tsx, which define how each brick type block, data, expression, statement is displayed and interacted with during development. For example, BrickBlock.tsx handles the rendering of block bricks, such as functions and loops, while BrickData.tsx focuses on rendering data bricks that store variable values. BrickData.tsx and BrickStatement.tsx manage the rendering of expression and statement bricks,which deal with mathematical operations and actions like loops or function calls. BrickWrapper.tsx is a higher-order component that ensures the proper rendering of all these bricks. Alongside these components, the TypeScript files (brickBlock.ts, brickData.ts, brickExpression.ts, brickStatement.ts) provide the necessary logic and functionality for each brick type, defining their properties, methods, and interactions within the system.  
      **iii. [masonry/src/brick/utils](https://github.com/sugarlabs/musicblocks-v4/tree/gsoc-2024/week-11-12/modules/masonry/src/brick/utils)**: This folder includes two key files:  
      **path.ts**: defines utility functions to generate SVG paths with precise dimensions and positions, using private helpers and public path assembly functions.  
      **path.spec.ts**: tests these utilities to ensure accuracy and handle edge cases reliably.

      **c. [Stack](https://github.com/sugarlabs/musicblocks-v4/tree/gsoc-2024/week-11-12/modules/masonry/src/stack) \-** The data.ts file in the stack module defines the logic for managing and interacting with the stack structure used in MusicBlocks. It contains the interface, representing nodes in the stack, and the IStack interface, which defines the stack's operations, such as adding, removing, moving, and validating nodes. The stack structure allows bricks (such as BrickModelData, BrickModelExpression, BrickModelStatement and BrickModelBlock) to be organized hierarchically, supporting nested and dynamic structures. The file also includes the implementation of the StackNode and Stack classes, which encapsulate the behavior of nodes and stacks respectively. The Stack class provides methods for manipulating and validating the stack, handling tasks like collapsing and expanding block nodes, and checking connection validity between nodes.

2. [**/masonry/playground**](https://github.com/sugarlabs/musicblocks-v4/tree/gsoc-2024/week-11-12/modules/masonry/playground) \- The **playground/** folder in the Masonry module serves as an interactive environment within MusicBlocks v4, designed to visualize and manipulate various types of bricks, such as blocks, data, expressions, and statements. It contains essential files like workspace/ which is the main page for rendering the interactive brick components, and houses components such as BrickBlock.tsx (for general-purpose blocks like loops and functions),  
   BrickData.tsx (for data storage), BrickExpression.tsx (for operations and expressions), BrickFactory.tsx (which dynamically selects and renders the correct brick type), and BrickStatement.tsx (for action-based bricks). Additionally, BrickStore.ts manages brick positions, while data.ts provides initialization data for rendering, and index.tsx serves as the entry point for initializing and coordinating the rendering process. The folder also includes utils.ts for helper functions that optimize rendering and state management, with index.html providing the base HTML structure and index.tsx bootstrapping the React components for dynamic user interaction. Together, these files facilitate a seamless interactive testing and experimentation platform for MusicBlocks v4.

At the core of **MusicBlocks-v4** lies **MusicBlocks-v4-lib**, a TypeScript library that defines the core logic and execution model of the entire platform. This library handles how each programming block behaves, whether it's a sound instruction, a control flow block, or a mathematical expression. It's essentially the "brain" of the system, responsible for interpreting and running the musical programs built in the visual editor. This makes it a critical foundation for the masonry module, which provides the drag-and-drop interface users interact with.

The connection between the two is thoughtfully structured:

- **Block behavior**: Every visual block in masonry maps to a corresponding element in MusicBlocks-v4-lib, ensuring that what you see in the editor has meaning under the hood.
- **Program structure**: As users arrange blocks visually, masonry builds an abstract syntax tree (AST) using classes from the library—capturing both the hierarchy and logic of the program.
- **Running programs**: When a project is executed, the AST is handed off to the library’s Interpreter, which walks through each block, step by step, and triggers its behavior.
- **Dynamic palette**: The list of available blocks in masonry comes directly from the library’s syntax registry, keeping the interface in sync with what's actually supported.
- **Managing state**: The library also helps manage runtime state—tracking instances of blocks, variables, and other execution data.

This setup keeps things clean and flexible:masonry takes care of the visual side, while **MusicBlocks-v4-lib** ensures everything works as expected behind the scenes. The separation makes it easier to develop and improve each part independently, while still working seamlessly together.

**Epic 1: Brick**

Bricks are the fundamental building blocks and the smallest unit of logic present in MusicBlocks. There are 4 fundamental brick types that define these constraints:

1. **Data Bricks** \- These Bricks represent variables and are further differentiated into Hardcoded Data Bricks(Represent fixed values that are set by the system and cannot be altered by the user) and Editable Data Bricks (Contain user-defined values that can be modified).
2. **Expression Bricks** \- These bricks accept one or more inputs (typically data bricks or expressions) and return a computed output
3. **Statement Bricks** \- Statement bricks define discrete actions or operations in the program flow.
4. **Block Bricks** \- Block bricks are a subtype of statement bricks that can contain nested bricks.

   **Goals**

5. **By supplying a configuration object that defines type, UI, inputs, and optional logic, the Masonry Framework should be able to render and initialize any valid brick dynamically for the user:**  
   **Functional Specs →**

The possible configuration objects are:  
**a. Brick Type** \- The Brick type should be either one of Data, Expression, Statement, Block Brick.  
**b. Brick ID / Name** \- Each brick shall have its own unique Brick ID/ name.  
**c. Display Label** \- This is the text or icon that shall display upon the brick in the UI.  
**d. Argument Definitions** \- The argument type of each editable brick shall be defined. Also the bricks should clearly be distinguishable whether it is editable or not.  
**e. Input/Output Ports** \- These are the visual connectors that show where other bricks can attach according to logic.  
**f. Editable Properties** \- The bricks can have inline text fields or dropdowns which the user can change.  
**g. Connection Rules** \- We shall also have a set of connection rules to define the brick connections that are done by the user.  
**Technical Specs →**  
MusicBlocks-v4 establishes a type-safe, interface-based framework for dynamically rendering bricks according to their configuration. Bricks are differentiated by kind (instruction or argument) and type (data, expression, statement, block), each with rendering properties such as labels, icons, colors, and layout (TExtent, TCoords). Instruction bricks allow for stack and nesting connections, whereas argument bricks allow for editable inputs in the form of text fields or dropdowns. All brick types have some renderProps that determine their appearance and behavior in the UI.  
**High Level Implementation →**  
To achieve this, we will create a generic component to understand a brick's config and type to determine its shape, styling, and input structure. The component will render dynamically using several different props; including renderProps, labelArgs, and bounding box data. The connection logic, editable inputs, and folding condition will act based on the brick's interface and its runtime state from Zustand.

2. **Users should be able to connect and disconnect bricks using Visual Support Anchors:**  
   **Functional Specs →**  
   Users should be able to visually connect and disconnect bricks in the workspace by dragging from one brick’s anchor point (input/output port) to another. When a valid connection is formed, the bricks visually snap together and update the execution flow. Users can also disconnect bricks by dragging them away or using context menu actions. This interaction should be intuitive and reversible.  
   **Technical Specs →**  
   In the codebase, bricks expose their fixed connection points via the connPointsFixed getter in the IBrick and IBrickInstruction interfaces. Each connection point includes a bounding box (TExtent) and relative coordinates (TCoords), allowing the system to detect proximity-based drag targets. For block-type bricks, additional connection points like insTop, insBottom, and insNest are defined for nesting and stacking via a refined connPointsFixed override. The engine is responsible for validating the logical compatibility of connections (e.g., type safety or execution structure).  
   **High Level Implementation →**  
   We will implement connection logic by enabling bricks to expose their anchor coordinates and accept incoming connections conditionally. As users drag a brick near another, the system will detect overlap using bounding box comparison. When a connection is dropped, the system will query the Engine to validate compatibility. If valid, the connection is committed in Zustand under an array and the brick layout is updated. Disconnecting will involve removing the reference from state and re-rendering the affected bricks.  

3. **Bricks should be styled specifically according to their basic configurations:**  
   **Functional Specs →**  
   **a. Shape Differentiation** **\-**  
   The spatial shape of a brick communicates its type and behavior:

- Data bricks: Tiny, pill or slot-shaped, intended to be nested within other bricks.
- Expression bricks: Tabbed to nest as arguments, visually contained within other blocks.
- Statement bricks: Full-width with rounded corners, signifying a step in linear flow.
- Block bricks: Big with indented insides to accommodate nested statements or loops.  
  **b. Color States \-**  
  Bricks alter color according to interaction and system state:
- Original Color: In config, set by type of bricks (e.g., yellow for control, green for math).
- Hover Color: The hover color should be a more saturated or bright version to highlight interactivity.
- Disconnected Color: The color should be faded to show there is no execution linkage.
- Execution Color: We can have a flash or glow visual effect when a program is executing for real-time feedback.  
  **c. Labels and Ports \-**
- Function Labels \- These labels are text written inside the brick to indicate its action, Argument Labels \- Placeholders or prompts that show where users must supply input
- Ports – Input ports will take values or statements. Output ports will return data or chaining. Ports must be visually different and uniformly located per type.  
  **d. Inline Editable Fields \-** Bricks shall contain editable UI elements which are Text Inputs (e.g., variable names, durations), Dropdowns (e.g., instrument selection)  
  **Technical Specs →**  
  The path.ts utility is a dedicated module for generating SVG path strings that define the visual shapes of bricks in the masonry layout. It takes geometric parameters (like width, height, corner radius) and converts them into SVG path commands. The file includes helper functions to build path segments such as lines and curves for rounded corners. Its core purpose is to abstract SVG path complexity and provide a programmatic interface for creating accurate visual representations based on brick configurations. SVG paths follow a specific syntax using commands like M (move to), L (line to), and C (cubic bezier curve). We will be making changes in this file by allotting different colors and shapes for brick types.,m k  
  **High Level Implementation →**  
  In the configuration for each brick, we will include a style object to define the shape, base color, hover / active / disconnected states, and port layout for that brick. The component will evaluate and render the appropriate geometry and color dynamically using the type and style fields, along with conditionally showing editable fields and labels based upon args and config flags. The visual representation for interaction states such as hover and execution will cause updates to the visual representation using either class toggles or inline style transitions. 4. **Different Bricks can have context menus specific to the specific brick:**  
   **Functional Specs →**  
   Bricks in MusicBlocks-v4 should support context-specific menus that expose additional options based on the brick’s purpose and complexity. Basic bricks offer inline editing through simple fields like text inputs or numbers, while advanced bricks can display a contextual menu accessible via right-click that includes toggles, dropdowns, or advanced configurations.  
   **Technical Specs →**  
   Each brick’s config will define a menu field that lists contextual UI elements such as input types, labels, and default values. In the codebase, editable fields are tied to args, and conditional UI like dropdowns or toggles are rendered based on the menu config structure. Inline inputs are handled inside the \<Brick /\> component, while the contextual menu is rendered via a floating menu component triggered on interaction.  
   **High Level Implementation →**  
   We’ll extend the \<Brick /\> component to show inline editors and trigger a floating context menu on right-click. Menu items will be generated dynamically from a menu field in the brick’s config. Inputs and toggles will update brick state through Zustand for real-time interactivity.  

5. **MusicBlocks-v4 should support a set of brick-level utility actions, accessible via right-click context menus:**  
   **Functional Specs →**  
   Such actions extend beyond editing and allow users to work with bricks effectively in building programs.  
   Core functionalities include:  
   **a. Duplicate** \- Instantly creates a copy of the selected brick, preserving its configuration and optionally its children.  
   **b. Extract** \- Removes a brick from its parent block or nesting container while keeping it intact in the workspace.  
   **c. Trash** \- Deletes the selected brick (or block of bricks), similar to dragging it into the workspace trash zone.  
   **Technical Specs →**  
   These actions will operate on the brick's instance data stored in the application state and will require access to the brick tree structure to preserve or update relationships (e.g., parent-child hierarchy). Utility functions will handle the logic for cloning, detaching, or removing brick instances, ensuring consistency in both the UI and internal program representation (AST).  
   **High Level Implementation →**  
   During implementation, right-clicking a brick will open a context menu with the available utility actions. On selecting Duplicate, a new instance will be created with a fresh ID, preserving the original brick’s config and optionally its children. Extract will detach the brick from its parent (if nested) and reposition it in the top-level workspace layer. Trash will remove the selected brick (and its children, if any) from the state entirely.  

6. **MusicBlocks-v4 should allow users to switch between related brick types directly within the workspace:**  
   **Functional Specs →**  
   The users should be able to to switch between related brick types directly within the workspace(e.g. switching between if and if-else, or pitch with octave/hertz etc).This can be presented as a dropdown, toggle on the brick itself, depending on how variants are grouped.  
   **Technical Specs →**  
   Switchable types of bricks (e.g. if ↔ if-else, pitch unit variations) will be specified through a variants field in every brick's configuration. This will contain an array of compatible brick IDs that can substitute the current one. The switch UI will come in the form of a dropdown or toggle that is embedded in the brick's UI. Upon selection, the system will update the type of the brick with the new version, keeping position, common arguments, children (if applicable), and ID references intact in the AST. State changes would be managed in Zustand by updating the map of brick instances and performing a re-render with the new config.  
   **High Level Implementation →**  
   When a user selects a new variant, a handler will create a new brick instance of the selected type, copy over shared fields (e.g. args, position, children), and replace the current instance in the Zustand store. The AST builder will reflect the change automatically by referencing the updated instance.

**Epic 2: Stack**

The Stack epic defines the behavior, validation, and interaction of connected bricks in the form of structured logic flows. A stack is a vertically connected chain of bricks that executes sequentially or conditionally, and may include nested structures.  
We can take inspiration for designing the stack from the current stack present in Musicblocks 3:  
![][image6]

**Goals**

1. **Generating a clean AST (Abstract Syntax Tree) from the bricks connected in the workspace:**  
   **Functional Specs →**  
   Users must be able to define programs graphically by linking bricks in the workspace, and have the system automatically create a corresponding Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) in the background. This AST is the logical program structure in a normalized, hierarchical form. When the user saves, executes, or exports their program, the system must serialize all linked bricks beginning from top-level entries and record each brick's type, arguments, nested children, and associated metadata.  
   **Technical Specs →**  
   The AST generator will walk the connected brick graph held in Zustand and emit a tidy, JSON-serializable tree that is the program's logic. Every BrickInstance holds vital metadata brickId, type, args, and children that are used to recreate the shape. It will start walking from root-level bricks (no parent or inbound connections) and recursively traverse each child or attached brick. The structure of the AST node will have fields for type, args, children, and optionally id or metadata, and will meet the expectations of the Engine module for execution or export.  
   **High Level Implementation →**  
   Implementation will include a recursive method that accepts a list of root brick IDs from the workspace state and builds a tree by resolving each brick's config and children. Along the traverse, inputs and editable fields are serialized into an args object, and block-type bricks recursively serialize their nested children. The AST will be returned as a stored, loadable, or passable structured JSON object. This logic will reside in a utility module attached to the workspace and will be invoked on save/export or program run.  

2. **The user should have a feature to fold/unfold block-type bricks:**  
   **Functional Specs →**  
   This feature enables users to fold blocks holding other bricks and is useful in complicated pieces where the screen can soon get cluttered with nested sequences and logic. When a block is folded, all its child bricks are out of sight, and the block is displayed in a minimized version. The UI must also show that the block is collapsed through a folded symbol of some sort. When toggled (through a click on the fold icon), the block expands and shows all of its nested contents in their original layout and order.  
   **Technical Specs →**  
   Fold/unfold behavior conditionally will be enabled for "type": "block" bricks or those with a children array as part of their AST definition. There will be an added folded boolean flag per BrickInstance within the Zustand store. This flag will be consumed by rendering logic within the brick component in determining whether child bricks should be rendered or hidden. Fold state will also be consulted during AST generation to correctly render hidden bricks.  
   **High Level Implementation →**  
   Each block-type brick will display a fold toggle icon (e.g., arrow or chevron) in its header. On click, the icon will trigger a handler that updates the folded state in Zustand for that brick’s instance. If folded, child bricks are visually hidden but remain in the state tree and AST. When unfolded, they are rendered in their original layout. This interaction will be implemented in the brick layout logic under the masonry module’s rendering layer.  

3. **MusicBlocks-v4 should support automatic height adjustment of parent bricks based on the dimensions of their child bricks:**  
   **Functional Specs →**  
   Any block-style brick with nested elements will dynamically resize to completely encase its inner content to grow or shrink as children are added, removed, or restructured. In contrast to MusicBlocks 3, where the parent height is set and can visually overlap or clip child content.  
   **Technical Specs →**  
   The resizing behavior will be applied to blocks of type "block" that have nested children. The layout system will listen for changes in a block's children array in Zustand and recalculate its visual height accordingly. It can be managed with a hybrid method: automatic resizing through ResizeObserver (for DOM-based) or manual bounding box recalculation (for canvas/custom rendering). Size changes will cause re-renders on impacted parents so that dimensions remain in sync across nested levels.  
   **High Level Implementation →**  
   Each block element will listen for its children's rendered height. Upon the structure adjustment because of child addition, removal, or mutation a layout effect will cause a recalculation of the parent height. This will either be taken care of by DOM resize observation or manually calculated based on brick position and spacing logic. Parent bricks will update size state and cause recursive upward layout adjustments.  

4. **The users should have real-time visual and contextual feedback during brick connections**:  
   **Functional Specs →**  
   Whenever a user tries to connect one brick to another either by dropping it near an input, chaining it in a stack, or injecting it into a block the system should validate the action in real time. It checks for issues such as:

- Missing required inputs
- incompatible types (e.g., connecting a statement to an argument slot)
- orphaned bricks that are not connected to any execution flow.  
  This validation should be triggered on events like dropping a brick, editing parameters, or manually disconnecting a connection. When a connection is invalid, the system should:
- Visually mark the affected brick (e.g., red border, warning icon)
- display a floating tooltip or inline message describing the issue in plain language (e.g., This brick needs a number input for ‘duration’).

**Technical Specs →**  
The system will confirm brick connections in real time through a connection validator module that intercepts drag-and-drop and editing events. The validator will ensure that there are no problems with missing required inputs, incompatible types of connections, and abandoned logic blocks. Validation rules will be established in the configuration of the brick (e.g., input types to expect, fields that are required) and applied through logic layered within the workspace interaction system. When a rule is broken, visual feedback such as a red border, error icons, and tooltips will be displayed through the UI layer.  
**High Level Implementation →**  
During connection attempts, the workspace will invoke a validator function that accepts source and target instances of bricks and checks them against pre-defined connection rules. This will be done on drop, on parameter updates, and on disconnection. If a violation is found, a validationError flag and error message will be added to the corresponding brick's state in Zustand. The rendering layer will monitor this state and refresh the UI with visual indicators (e.g., red border) and floating hints via light error overlays.

**Epic 3: Workspace**

The Workspace is a flexible, grid-based canvas where users visually construct programs by dragging, placing, and connecting bricks. It serves as the primary interaction layer for composing logic, nesting blocks, and managing execution flow.

**Goals**

1. **The user shall be able to drag and drop brick into the workspace and move it around:**  
   **Functional Specs →**  
   Users should be able to drag bricks from the palette into the workspace and move them around freely. When a brick is dropped, it should appear immediately in the workspace with the correct shape, label, and inputs as defined by its configuration. Bricks should remain movable and interactive post-drop, enabling users to adjust layout without friction. This is the core user interaction model that powers visual programming in MusicBlocks-v4.

**Technical Specs →**  
The drag-and-drop functionality will be implemented using Zustand for state management. Upon drag start, the draggingBrickId is stored in state. Upon drop on the workspace, a new instance of the brick object is created with:

- A unique instanceId
- Its brickId (from config)
- (x, y) drop coordinates
- An args object pre-populated with default input values  
  This example is added to an array in Zustand. The position is live updated as the user drags the brick so that there is complete two-way syncing between the UI and state.  
  **High Level Implementation →**  
  The palette triggers a drag event that stores the selected brickId. On drop in the workspace, a handler creates a new brick instance and adds it to state. The brick is rendered using a generic \<Brick /\> component, which pulls config from the registry and positional data from the instance state. Each brick container listens to pointer/mouse events to support repositioning, and on drag, updates its x, y coordinates in Zustand. Positioning aligns with the grid system, and updates to state automatically trigger re-renders for smooth, responsive interaction.  


2. **MusicBlocks-v4 should have buttons around the start block to run only that thread, go step by step and go slowly:**  
   **Functional Specs →**  
   These buttons allow users to run a single thread independently, without triggering the entire workspace. The controls include:  
   **Run This Thread**: This button should execute only the branch beginning from this start brick.  
   **Run Step By Step**: This button shall execute one brick at a time in sequence, highlighting execution flow.  
   **Run Slowly**: This button will execute the thread at a reduced speed, helpful for observing changes and debugging logic.

**Technical Specs →**  
Button visibility and styling must be treated contextually i.e. only appearing on hover or on selection of a start block to keep the UI clean. The workspace will offload actual logic and timing control to an external config system. The Workspace module has only to be concerned with drawing the buttons, invoking the right actions, and maintaining visual state (e.g., highlighting active bricks).  
**High Level Implementation →**  
On hover or selection of a start brick, the workspace will render control buttons (Run, Step, Slow) as overlays anchored to the brick. Clicking a button dispatches a corresponding action to the external execution engine. The workspace listens for feedback (e.g., active brick IDs) to visually highlight the executing bricks during the process.

3. **Bricks and blocks of bricks should not overlap when placed or moved within the workspace:**  
   **Functional Specs →**  
   When a user drops a new brick or drags an existing brick into the workspace, the system needs to determine if its location would overlap with another brick. If there is an overlap, the system should either auto-shift the position of the brick to snap it onto the closest non-overlapping available space or should refuse the drop and display a visual hint (e.g., red border).

**Technical Specs →**  
In order to avoid overlapping bricks in the workspace, the system will include a collision detection mechanism when performing drag-and-drop. This functionality will be located within the brick layout and movement handling code at masonry/src/brick/design0, which already has layout and shape definitions. A bounding box will be exposed by each brick based on its dimensions and position. During dragging, these boxes would be compared on the fly against all other ongoing bricks to sense possible overlaps. A grid arrangement or flow format policy will simply be applied to move the brick to the nearest valid position. Visual feedback (e.g., a red border) will be initiated through class changes or local state flags on sensing a collision.  
**High Level Implementation →**  
During implementation, each brick’s dimensions and position will be tracked within its layout state. When a user drags a brick, its projected bounding box will be checked against others using a lightweight axis-aligned bounding box (AABB) collision check. This logic will run inside the drag handler system already scaffolded in the workspace renderer. If an overlap is detected, the system will either snap the brick to a nearby non-conflicting position using a simple grid resolver or block the drop entirely and show a visual warning. This will ensure all bricks remain legible, interactive, and non-overlapping regardless of workspace density.

4. **Users should be able to delete bricks/blocks of bricks by dragging them to a corner of the workspace:**  
   **Functional Specs →**  
   Users should be able to delete single bricks or whole blocks by dragging them into an available trash zone(usually a corner of the workspace). While a brick is being dragged, the trash zone becomes highlighted. When the brick is dropped over this area, the brick is removed from the workspace permanently. This gesture allows for an easy means of removing content, particularly with nested content.

**Technical Specs →**  
The trash zone will be a fixed UI component drawn inside the workspace layer. Its bounding box will be utilized for collision detection during drag. When a brick is dragged, its coordinates are constantly compared with the trash area bounds. If the drop is within that region, the system triggers a deleteBrickInstance() action in the Zustand store, which also deletes child bricks recursively (if it's a block). Hover effect over the trash area gives visual feedback (e.g., highlight or change of color) when a draggable brick moves into the area.  
**High Level Implementation →**  
During drag, the workspace tracks the brick’s live position and checks for overlap with the trash zone area. On drop, if the brick is within the zone, it triggers a state update that removes the brick (and children if applicable) from the Zustand-managed workspace state. The UI updates immediately to reflect the deletion.

5. **Users should be able to scale blocks in the workspace:**  
   **Functional Specs →**

6. **Users should be able to add inline comments and debug breakpoints within the workspace:**  
   **Functional Specs →**

      **Technical Specs →**

Comments are stored as editable text fields linked by brickId, allowing annotations for logic explanation or notes. Breakpoints are tracked using a flag per brick and are used to signal execution pauses to the Engine. Both features rely on external modules for saving, restoring, or responding to execution events, while Masonry handles state management, display, and interaction.  
  **High Level Implementation →**  
  Users insert comments or toggle breakpoints through a right-click menu or inline icons on every brick. At runtime, the Engine halts on breakpointed bricks and emits feedback events that Masonry picks up on, updating visual highlights accordingly. The workspace controls the UI while execution and persistence are managed by external modules.

7. **Users should have access to buttons around the start block to run only that thread, go step by step and go slowly:**  
   **Functional Specs →**  
   These buttons allow users to run a single thread independently, without triggering the entire workspace. The controls include:  
   **Run This Thread**: This button should execute only the branch beginning from this start brick.  
   **Run Step By Step**: This button shall execute one brick at a time in sequence, highlighting execution flow.

The Workspace module has only to be concerned with drawing the buttons, invoking the right actions, and maintaining visual state (e.g., highlighting active bricks).  
   **High Level Implementation →**  
   Whenever a user hovers over or clicks on a start block, the workspace will display a contextual control panel with three buttons: Run, Step, and Slow. These three buttons will be placed relative to the brick and styled lightly in order to not draw too much attention. On clicking any button, an external execution handler (for example, runThread(startId), stepThread(startId), runThreadSlow(startId)) will be called, passing the brickId of the corresponding thread. The workspace waits for execution events to reshow visual cues—like active brick highlights while timing, sequencing, and control logic is all taken care of outside in the Engine module.

**Epic 4: Palette**

The Palette is a scrollable, categorized panel that shows all available bricks in categories by type (Data, Expression, Statement, Block) and enables users to preview, search, and drag them into the workspace. It can include visual cues such as icons and color coding, real-time filtering by search, and smooth drag-and-drop operations.  
For how the UI of the palette is going to look we can take inspiration from the palette in [Scratch](https://scratch.mit.edu/).  
![][image8]

**Goals:**

1. **A list of Bricks shall be available (palette) shall be available for the users to choose specific bricks from:**  
   **Functional Specs →**

- The Palette will be docked on the left side of the workspace and will remain persistently visible during editing to provide quick access to bricks.
- Bricks will be presented in a categorized vertical list, grouped by type
- Each group will be contained within a collapsible panel for better navigation.
- When a user selects or searches for a specific brick type, the palette will automatically scroll to the corresponding category section. This helps in quick discovery without manual scrolling.
- Each brick entry in the list will include:

  - The brick’s label
  - A type-specific color or styling
  - An optional icon for visual distinction
  - A hover effect to indicate interactivity

        **Technical Specs →**

    The palette will be a bottom, vertically scrollable frame along the left edge of the workspace. It will show the bricks categorized by their type Data, Expression, Statement, and Block. Bricks will be rendered in accordance with external configuration, each item having a name, icon, and type-specific appearance. The color scheme will provide programmatic scrolling based on equivalent logic when a user searches or chooses a particular type of brick. Custom blocks (user-defined subroutines) will be inserted into another "Custom" section. Local or global state will be utilized for storing expanded sections, scroll position, and live filtering.  
    **High Level Implementation →**  
    The palette component will render on the left and initialize with categorized brick groups loaded from a config registry. Each section will be tied to a DOM ref, allowing automatic scrolling to a section when triggered. Users can drag bricks directly from the palette into the workspace. When a search term or brick type is selected, the system identifies the matching category or brick and scrolls to it. Interactions like hover, selection, and category toggling will update UI state and optionally persist between sessions.

2. **The user should have a search functionality for bricks in the palette that allows users to instantly filter bricks by name and type:**  
   **Functional Specs →**  
   The search field must be placed at the top of the palette panel and offer real-time filtering as the user types. Matching bricks must be visible, while non-matching bricks are hidden or dimmed. Optionally, search terms can be highlighted in matching bricks to visually guide the user. Search must match against:

- brick names(e.g., note)
- types of bricks(e.g., Data Bricks, Statement Bricks)

**Technical Specs →**  
The search field will consist of a controlled input located at the top of the palette component. Every time the user types a keystroke, the search term will be retained in component or global state (e.g., Zustand or React state). The bricks will be filtered to be a simple substring match with no case sensitivity with both the brick's name and the brick's type or category label. Any bricks that matched will be flagged for display, while bricks that didn't match each search term will be hidden or rendered with lower opacity. For better visibility, each match could be highlighted with a utility that wraps matching sub strings in tags with a highlight class. The filtering logic will be debounced for input handling and provide optimal UI performance for larger palettes.  
**High Level Implementation →**  
As the user types into the search field, the palette dynamically filters brick entries by comparing the input against brick names and their category types. The component conditionally renders only the matching bricks, preserving category groupings when possible. If all bricks within a group are filtered out, that section can collapse automatically or remain hidden. To improve readability, the matching portion of the brick name can be highlighted using inline JSX markup.

**Some other deliverables that I will be working upon are:**

**Write Storybook stories to document and showcase UI components →** Each brick type will have a Storybook story to showcase different scenarios using factory functions for dynamic rendering. Stories help us preview and test bricks with varying labels, arguments, and styles to ensure consistent UI and solid design choices. Each story exports a Meta object for config and uses StoryObj to define rendering props. They will cover new features like argument slots, nesting containers, and user interactions. Visual parameters (e.g., colors, scale) in stories help catch UI bugs and guide design decisions.

**Implement unit tests for functions and classes using Vitest →**  
We're using Vitest in MusicBlocks-v4 for its compatibility with Vite \+ TypeScript and support for Jest-style syntax.Our focus will be on core logic like SVG path creation (path.ts), brick interfaces (index.ts), and utility functions for adding, deleting, nesting, or cloning bricks. These tests ensure stability, catch bugs early, and make refactoring safer. I’ve also implemented tests in MusicBlocks 3, which gives me a strong foundation for this work.

**Export a minimal API for integration with other parts of the application →** We are going to export a basic API to allow easy access to important functions, like program structure, brick manipulation, and rendering data, without requiring any of the internal logic. Think of the basic API as a buffer between the core logic and other components (e.g. UI, renderer or editor). This architecture will increase modularity and allow for easier integration, testing, and refactoring without having a negative impact on the other pieces of the application.

**Produce developer documentation to describe main modules, data structures, and APIs→** We will document core modules, structures, and APIs to make MusicBlocks-v4 easier to understand and maintain. Clear documentation will help developers navigate interactions like brick rendering and program logic with ease. This will speed up development, support future contributions, and ensure long-term stability.
